#if(v_toughness < 4) {
 

Before I get to finish my train of thought, two smaller boulders pass through both Daren and Melindra's barriers with ease, and one of them hits me in the head before I even get the time to realize what's going on.

The impact of the hit cracks my skull in an instant, as my consciousness slowly fades away.

}
#if(v_toughness >= 4) {
 

Before I get to finish my train of thought, two smaller boulders pass through both Daren and Melindra's barriers with ease, and one of them hits me in the head before I even get the time to realize what's going on.

The pain I'm feeling right now is pretty bad and I'm almost certain that I will be getting a bump on my head because of this, but if my toughness stat were any lower, my skull could have easily cracked, so I guess I should be thankful that I'm still alive.

I should not have gotten so relaxed back there. I need to remember that this is still the middle of a battlefield. If I make another blunder like that, it may well prove fatal. I can't afford to get lost in my own thoughts like this again.

"Barry, are you alive?!" Kate says, sounding slightly panicked, as she quickly makes a somewhat transparent ice dome around us.

"I'm fine..." I say. "My head hurts a little, but I'm fine. My toughness stat really saved me back there. I'm really glad that I put some points into it."  

 "I'll try to keep up the pressure on the captain while I maintain the dome, but it won't be easy," Kate says. "Don't be too surprised if he manages to retaliate soon."

"Actually, Kate," Daren says, as he points towards the sky, where about a hundred or more huge boulders are preparing to rain down upon us, "I think you should give up on the captain and put everything you've got into fortifying your ice dome. My barrier's beginning to reach its limit, and wind barriers aren't all that good against rocks, as you've no doubt already realized by now. Also, if the earth elementalist will send a few more regular rocks like those two from earlier, your dome will be the only reliable defense we have against them."

"Very well," Kate says. "I will focus all of my efforts on defense, then. Let's hope we won't come to regret this decision later."

She then begins to pour as much magical energy into her ice dome as she can, making it a lot more opaque in the process. It is harder now to see what is going on outside our shelter, but once the boulders start hitting the ice dome we can easily tell exactly what's happening.

 The rocks just keep coming one after the other, but Kate's reinforced ice is still holding strong. We can almost sense the earth elementalist's frustration, as he keeps hitting the dome across its whole surface, trying to find any kind of weak point. He even sends ten consecutive boulders in the exact same spot once, in the hopes that Kate won't be able to recreate and reinforce the ice fast enough to block them. In the end, none of his tactics work and although Kate's dome looks as if it were ready to crumble any minute, the rocks from the sky are no longer falling, presumably because after all this time the earth elementalist finally ran out of ammo.

Just as we are about to relax a little, the ice dome above us gets destroyed completely and then we feel the captain's aura pushing us into the ground with a greater force than ever before.

}
